SIMPLE: portcullis
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Portcullis
<hw>Port*cul"lis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>porte
coulisse</ets>, <ets>cole⟦ium⟧ce</ets>, a sliding door, fr. L.
<ets>colare</ets>, <ets>colatum</ets>, to filter, to strain: cf. F.
<ets>couler</ets> to glide. See <er>Port</er> a gate, and cf.
<er>Cullis</er>, <er>Colander</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>A grating of iron or of timbers pointed with
iron, hung over the gateway of a fortress, to be let down to prevent the
entrance of an enemy.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Let the <xex>portcullis</xex>
fall.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She . . . the huge <qex>portcullis</qex> high updrew.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An English coin of the reign of Elizabeth, struck
for the use of the East India Company; -- so called from its bearing the
figure of a portcullis on the reverse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Portcullis</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Portcullis
<hw>Port*cul"lis</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Portcullised</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Portcullising</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To obstruct with, or as
with, a portcullis; to shut; to bar.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Porte</ent>⟦br⟧
